<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=12906#M12906">207</a> of 369
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2572 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div>I don't like to be wholey negative if I can help it... so I
will praise the willingness of players to take the time to write in
depth responses to the initial question.
<br>
<br>
That being said this thread from a development standpoint is at best a
publicity event. At worse its an open statement of questionable
competence.
The listed variables from different classes are inherently connected to
balance issues. E.g. that enchanters value AC more than wizards, and
wizards mana regen more than enchanters is obvious but should not
impact itemization as those classes (and their style of play) are
balanced upon the shared limitation in those areas. Shifting
itemization based upon players natural desire to differntiate their
class into the stronger fullfillment of niche role performance in a
game that due to the number of available classes, and lack of roles for
same, is antithetical to proper design.
<br>
<br>
Some good questions would have been:
what examples of itemization do you as a player find to be illogical?
are their gaps in itemization that you find unduly burden a players progression, if so what?
etc...

<br>
<br>
In closing I am in agreement with the former critic. The breadth of
current effect areas in EQ itemization is such that hard analysis is
required. The following response from the "benevolent dictator" with a
cutesy smiley at the end was hardly a compelling rebuttal. First
impressions are often not reliable, but this new itemization era of EQ
has appeared to be that of 'the cool new dude', rather than that of a
competent analytical mind.<p>Message Edited by Kether-Eci on <span class=date_text>07-09-2006</span> <span class=time_text>08:07 AM</span>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
