<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=12908#M12908">209</a> of 369
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2501 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Kether-Eci wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>I don't like to be wholey negative if I can help it... so I will praise the willingness of players to take the time to write in depth responses to the initial question. <BR><BR>That being said this thread from a development standpoint is at best a publicity event. At worse its an open statement of questionable competence. The listed variables from different classes are inherently connected to balance issues. E.g. that enchanters value AC more than wizards, and wizards mana regen more than enchanters is obvious but should not impact itemization as those classes (and their style of play) are balanced upon the shared limitation in those areas. Shifting itemization based upon players natural desire to differntiate their class into the stronger fullfillment of niche role performance in a game that due to the number of available classes, and lack of roles for same, is antithetical to proper design. <BR><BR>Some good questions would have been: what examples of itemization do you as a player find to be illogical? are their gaps in itemization that you find unduly burden a players progression, if so what? etc... <BR><BR>In closing I am in agreement with the former critic. The breadth of current effect areas in EQ itemization is such that hard analysis is required. The following response from the "benevolent dictator" with a cutesy smiley at the end was hardly a compelling rebuttal. First impressions are often not reliable, but this new itemization era of EQ has appeared to be that of 'the cool new dude', rather than that of a competent analytical mind.
<P>Message Edited by Kether-Eci on <SPAN class=date_text>07-09-2006</SPAN> <SPAN class=time_text>08:07 AM</SPAN><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>How is asking the people who know their  classes the best a sign of incompetence?&nbsp; IMO not using all resources available to you is a sign of incompetence.&nbsp; Now admittedly, there is some filtering that needs to be done w/personal biases etc.</P>
<P>I don't believe that it is a bad thing for gear to compliment the design of a class.&nbsp; Wizards do need more&nbsp;tools&nbsp;for offense such as more mana regen than what a enchanter typically needs,&nbsp; whereas enchanters do need more defensive tools such as more AC, having those options in itemization would allow esp for caster diversity.&nbsp; Now should enchanters go around dressed in full plate, well no, of course not, but there is room for changes before we hit anywhere near that mark.</P>
<P>"Some good questions would have been: what examples of itemization do you as a player find to be illogical?"&nbsp; Pallies/sk can't use 2 weapons, berserkers must use 2 hands for every weapon,&nbsp; bards can't wield 2 handed weapons, and casters can lug around huge shields, but cast just fine moving them around..&nbsp; Bad question there if you ask me~</P>
<P>"are their gaps in itemization that you find unduly burden a players progression" -- Well in an indirect manner that's what he did.&nbsp; Instead of me telling him yeah wizards only get 3-5 pieces from each expansion to max thier power, which is 1 of the reasons wizard power is such a pity atm, all this other stuff is nothing but e-**SMURF** fluff, could you maybe, I don't know, do something about that?!&nbsp; He gave a fairly complete list so he could examine more or less raw data, so he can make decisions, instead of going off a very angled perspective from 16 different classes.</P>
<P>As far as I'm concerned, Itemization has been a failure since OoW, hardly any anaylsis have been made other than +5% improvements and let's standardize equipment&nbsp;(cookie cutters yay!! $$)&nbsp; I much rather have someone that is interested in players ideas (even if most won't be used) vs someone who just makes things that are status quo and moves on w/o blinking.</P>
<P>Sacora</P>	
