		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div><blockquote><hr>Sacora wrote:<br><br>As far as I'm concerned, Itemization has been a failure since OoW, hardly any anaylsis have been made other than +5% improvements and let's standardize equipment&nbsp;(cookie cutters yay!! $$)&nbsp; I much rather have someone that is interested in players ideas (even if most won't be used) vs someone who just makes things that are status quo and moves on w/o blinking.<br><br><hr></blockquote><br>Being interested in what the players think is great.&nbsp; Believing that asking a tiny subset of the player base to evaluate their own itemisation based on their own bias (you call it knowledge) when they actually have no access to the back-end mechanics or to the underlying development decisions which form the basis of balance (we as players *assume* a lot, and know very little about the back-end balancing act) is fraught with danger.<br><br>Bulletin Board users are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; People who answer questions about stats are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; You've got a self selecting sub-set of a self selecting sub-set providing you with data.&nbsp; It's not just skewed, it's going to be horrifically skewed.<br><br>There's a reason why data gathering techniques that yield valid results have methodologies behind them and why they do not rely on asking a self selecting set of people for their opinion.<br><br>Either the responses we're seeing are going to be ignored because they're far too variable and skewed to be valuable in which case it's publicity and pure curiosity, or they're going to be used in which case I'm appalled and concerned that design decisions are made on the basis of the opinion of a tiny sub-set of the EQ population.<br><br>I am all for more communication from and with the development team.&nbsp; The recent 'weekly question' is a classic example of failed communications and so is this post from The Itemizer.&nbsp; Both give false hope.<br><br></div>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							-- <br>Lock: "Goddamnit, Morpheus! Not everyone believes what you believe!"<br>Morpheus: "My beliefs do not require them to."
							</div>
								
