<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=12913#M12913">214</a> of 369
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2435 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Fzan_Torv wrote:<BR>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Being interested in what the players think is great.&nbsp; Believing that asking a tiny subset of the player base to evaluate their own itemisation based on their own bias (you call it knowledge) when they actually have no access to the back-end mechanics or to the underlying development decisions which form the basis of balance (we as players *assume* a lot, and know very little about the back-end balancing act) is fraught with danger.</DIV><FONT color=#009900></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><FONT color=#009900>Just an example, but what backend knowledge do I need to know that wizards and rogues are suppose to be the top dps classes, not necros or berzerkers?&nbsp;&nbsp;Yes, it would be fraught w/danger if classes all worked as they were intended, but alas nope.&nbsp; </FONT>
<DIV><BR><BR>Bulletin Board users are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; People who answer questions about stats are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; You've got a self selecting sub-set of a self selecting sub-set providing you with data.&nbsp; It's not just skewed, it's going to be horrifically skewed.<BR><BR>There's a reason why data gathering techniques that yield valid results have methodologies behind them and why they do not rely on asking a self selecting set of people for their opinion.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#006600>Who said this was a double blind study w/results ending in a seamless standard normal bell curve of responses (etc etc continue on w/stat jargon)? Just asking opinions of the playerbase, and quite frankly nothing out of unusual that I've seen.</FONT><BR><BR>Either the responses we're seeing are going to be ignored because they're far too variable and skewed to be valuable in which case it's publicity and pure curiosity, or they're going to be used in which case I'm appalled and concerned that design decisions are made on the basis of the opinion of a tiny sub-set of the EQ population.<BR></DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#006600>Reading the great majority of posts, I don't see much variation, and no skewed answers like bards should be able to do 10x rogues dmg. No requests for God-mode or anything.&nbsp; Yes, everyone should appalled if opinions of players are used, cause how dare they make the game enjoyable.&nbsp; And you don't think devs havn't taken a&nbsp;single person's&nbsp;opinion and used it, well think again that happened w/wizard's anguish robe, the focus could have been 55% dmg focus to acf&nbsp;or 25% mp to acf, and b/c someone liked bigger nukes vs more efficient nukes we got 55% dmg focus, which was very short-sighted on thier part.&nbsp; The handful of people who post&nbsp;is a greater sampling size than asking 1 person so that's a step up~</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;<BR>I am all for more communication from and with the development team.&nbsp; The recent 'weekly question' is a classic example of failed communications and so is this post from The Itemizer.&nbsp; Both give false hope.<BR><BR><FONT color=#006600>Why if any direct communication is biased is fubar'd?&nbsp; I'll agree that most attempts of dev interaction falls well short, but this is a new guy, I'm willing to give him a chance~</FONT></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>	
		</td></tr>
