		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Fzan_Torv wrote:
<DIV><BR>Being interested in what the players think is great.&nbsp; Believing that asking a tiny subset of the player base to evaluate their own itemisation based on their own bias (you call it knowledge) when they actually have no access to the back-end mechanics or to the underlying development decisions which form the basis of balance (we as players *assume* a lot, and know very little about the back-end balancing act) is fraught with danger.<BR><BR>Bulletin Board users are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; People who answer questions about stats are a *self selecting* set of people.&nbsp; You've got a self selecting sub-set of a self selecting sub-set providing you with data.&nbsp; It's not just skewed, it's going to be horrifically skewed.<BR></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Given that too small a sample size limits the validity of the data collected, pass this thread around to all of the other EQ-related bulletin boards you frequent, and get more people to respond, smoothing out the data by vast quantity.</P>
<P>Simple solution to your stated problem.</P>	
		</td></tr>
