		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div>Well itemization isnt about just basic stats and effects, its about how
pieces work together to form a complete package (kit).&nbsp; I had a
couple of beefs in particualar the Demiplane itemization. <br>
<br>
&nbsp;1) was STR stat was on the light side.&nbsp; So much so that if
you were to complete a demiplane kit as a beastlord you would find that
your strength was barely capped, while other stats would be over-capped
by margins in the hundreds if not few hundreds.&nbsp; Now, over-cap is
good .. for AE's and such, but there needs to be that overcap on STR as
well.<br>
<br>
2) same effect on multiple items that a person of a particular class
would want.&nbsp; For example, I think there are 3 items in Demiplane
that have Cleave VI on them.&nbsp; Its out of control.&nbsp; IMHO
people would want to upgrade from anguish level to demiplane level
mostly because overall its better hp / mana .. but the effects and foci
need to line up as well when somone is working on their upgrade path.<br>
<br>
3)&nbsp; Vermillion Bat Fur Sash.&nbsp; Only DPoB pet foci, and its on
a belt with marginal stats otherwise, particularly AC.&nbsp; In the
case of beastlords, myself and I think most people that came down the
same path were using Vish belt before hand.&nbsp; Pet Foci is a big
deal but the way things work right now is its only desireable for its
foci so most of the time its just equipped to summon the pet then Vish
belt is put back on.&nbsp; Other options for a DPoB pet foci would have
been nice, such as a ring or an ear, or wrist, or even better yet as an
effect on one of the DPoB augments.<br>
<br>
My advice to you when doing itemization is to know the classes and how
they think.&nbsp; Knowing whats important is a necessary first step,
but it has to go beyond that.&nbsp; I think its important to not judge
an item just in of itself and only compared to an item from&nbsp; a
previous
era, but to look at itemizations as a complete package that is
constantly evolving and get into the minds of how people like to
progress their gear and also the likely paths that they will be
upgrading their gear so that their complete package can stay as
relatively in balance while they are progressing.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br><p>Message Edited by Essant_LeFur on <span class=date_text>07-10-2006</span> <span class=time_text>12:28 PM</span>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
